  <bioghist encodinganalog="545"> 
  	<head>Biography of Hugo Butler</head><p>Hugo Butler began writing for the movies in Hollywood in 1937. He wrote screenplays for <emph>Huckleberry Finn</emph> (1939), <emph>Lassie Come Home</emph> (1943), and <emph>Robinson Crusoe</emph> (1954). He was nominated for an Academy Award for <emph>Edison the Man</emph> (1940). In 1951 Butler and his wife, Jean Rouverol, moved to Mexico as a result of blacklisting in Hollywood. Butler wrote documentary screenplays and worked with film director Luis Buñuel while in Mexico. For a time he lived in Italy to work on <emph>The Last Days of Sodom and Gomorrah</emph>.  In 1964 the family returned to California. Butler and Jean Rouverol were working together on the screenplay of <emph>The Legend of Lilah Clare</emph> when Butler died in 1968.</p>
	 
  </bioghist> 
  <scopecontent encodinganalog="520"> 
	 <head>Scope and Content</head><p>The Hugo Butler papers contain screenplays, reviews, and some publicity and production notes for motion pictures authored by Hugo Butler.</p>
	 
  </scopecontent> 
